1. Introduction

The Challenge of Music Discovery

Imagine standing in a record store with 100 million songs. How would you find music you'll love?
This is the daily challenge faced by modern streaming platforms like Spotify, Apple Music, and YouTube Music.

As of 2025, Spotify hosts over 100 million tracks, with tens of thousands more added every day. Without effective recommendation systems, this abundance becomes overwhelming, a phenomenon known as the paradox of choice.

Music recommendation systems solve this problem by acting as intelligent curators, analyzing patterns in audio features, user behavior, and social signals to connect listeners with songs theyll enjoy. According to industry research, over 30% of total streaming time on major platforms is driven by algorithmic recommendations, making these systems essential to both user experience and business success.

Why Music Recommendation Is Unique

Unlike recommending movies or books, music recommendation presents several unique challenges:

  • Short consumption time: A 3-minute song provides far less feedback signal than a 2-hour movie.
  • Context sensitivity: Users want different music when working out, studying, relaxing, or commuting.
  • Mood dependency: Preferences fluctuate with emotional state.
  • High replay value: People may listen to the same track hundreds of times.
  • Subjective audio qualities: Musical taste is deeply personal and difficult to quantify.

These challenges make music recommendation an ideal case study for understanding the complexities of intelligent information retrieval systems.

Data Science Pipeline Overview

This tutorial walks through the complete data science workflow:

Raw Data Cleaning Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) Feature Engineering Modeling Evaluation Insights

At each stage, we apply rigorous analytical methods while maintaining a focus on practical, real-world applicability.
The goal is not only to build models that run in a notebook, but also to understand principles that scale to production systems serving millions of users.

Learning Objectives

By the end of this tutorial, you will be able to:

  • Clean and preprocess large-scale music metadata
  • Conduct meaningful exploratory analysis on high-dimensional audio data
  • Implement and compare multiple recommendation algorithms
  • Evaluate recommendation quality using appropriate metrics
  • Understand trade-offs between accuracy, diversity, and scalability
  • Apply these techniques to other recommendation domains

About the Dataset

We use Spotifys 30,000 Songs Dataset from Kaggle, which contains rich metadata for approximately 30,000 tracks.
Each track includes:

Audio Features (9 total)

  • Danceability
  • Energy
  • Loudness
  • Speechiness
  • Acousticness
  • Instrumentalness
  • Liveness
  • Valence
  • Tempo

Metadata

  • Track name
  • Artist
  • Album
  • Popularity score

Genre Labels

  • Playlist genre
  • Playlist subgenre

These features come from Spotifys Audio Analysis API, which uses machine learning models to extract musical characteristics from raw audio.
For example:

  • Valence measures the musical positiveness of a track (happy vs. sad).
  • Danceability describes how suitable a track is for dancing, based on rhythm stability and beat strength.

Dataset Source

  • 30000 Spotify Songs on Kaggle:
    https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/joebeachcapital/30000-spotify-songs

  • Spotify Web API Documentation: Audio Features Reference:
    https://developer.spotify.com/documentation/web-api/reference/get-audio-features

2.3 Data Quality Assessment

Once data quality issues are identified, we apply a structured cleaning process to prepare the dataset for analysis and modeling.
Each step addresses a specific problem:

  • Removing duplicate tracks: Eliminates repeated track_id entries to prevent bias toward songs appearing in multiple playlists.
  • Resetting the index: Ensures indices are contiguous after deduplication, avoiding alignment issues during feature extraction and similarity calculations.
  • Handling missing values: Replaces missing text fields (track name, artist, album) with "Unknown" and imputes numerical values where necessary.
  • Creating a working copy: Preserves the original dataset in case we need to revisit cleaning decisions later.
In[8]:

Handling Missing Values

In[9]:
missing_cols = df_clean.columns[df_clean.isnull().any()].tolist()
display(Markdown(f"Columns with missing values: {missing_cols}"))

categorical_cols = [
    'track_name', 'track_artist', 'track_album_name', 
    'playlist_name', 'playlist_genre', 'playlist_subgenre'
]
for col in categorical_cols:
    if col in missing_cols:
        df_clean[col].fillna('Unknown', inplace=True)

numerical_cols = df_clean.select_dtypes(include=[np.number]).columns
for col in numerical_cols:
    if col in missing_cols:
        df_clean[col].fillna(df_clean[col].median(), inplace=True)

display(Markdown(f"Missing values after cleaning: {df_clean.isnull().sum().sum()}"))

df_spotify = df_clean.copy()

2.4 Feature Organization

To streamline analysis, we group features into logical categories:

  • Audio features: danceability, energy, valence, loudness, speechiness, acousticness, instrumentalness, liveness, tempo
  • Metadata: track name, artist, album, popularity, duration
  • Genre attributes: playlist genre and subgenre labels
  • Engineered features: composite metrics derived later in the workflow

Organizing features in this way helps maintain clarity as we perform EDA, build feature matrices, and train recommendation models.

3.3 Feature Correlation Analysis

Correlations reveal how audio features move together and help identify redundancy.

In[20]:
correlation_matrix = df_spotify[audio_features].corr()

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))
sns.heatmap(correlation_matrix, annot=True, fmt='.2f', cmap='coolwarm',
            center=0, square=True, linewidths=1, cbar_kws={"shrink": 0.8})
plt.title('Audio Features Correlation Matrix', fontsize=16, fontweight='bold', pad=20)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

high_corr = []
for i in range(len(correlation_matrix.columns)):
    for j in range(i+1, len(correlation_matrix.columns)):
        if abs(correlation_matrix.iloc[i, j]) > 0.5:
            high_corr.append({
                'Feature 1': correlation_matrix.columns[i],
                'Feature 2': correlation_matrix.columns[j],
                'Correlation': correlation_matrix.iloc[i, j]
            })

if high_corr:
    display(Markdown("#### Highly Correlated Features (|r| > 0.5)"))
    high_corr_df = pd.DataFrame(high_corr).sort_values('Correlation', ascending=False)
    display(high_corr_df)
else:
    display(Markdown("**No highly correlated features found (|r| > 0.5)**"))

Notable relationships:

  • Energy Loudness: r 0.68 louder tracks tend to be more energetic.
  • Energy Acousticness: r 0.55 highly energetic tracks are typically less acoustic.

These relationships indicate that certain features convey overlapping musical information, which affects how similarity metrics behave.

3.4 Genre-Specific Feature Profiles

Averaging audio features within each genre highlights distinct audio signatures.

Examples:

  • EDM: Very high energy, high tempo, low acousticness.
  • Latin: High danceability and valence (often upbeat).
  • R&B: Lower energy but smoother acoustic signatures.
  • Rap: High speechiness and rhythmic emphasis.
  • Rock: Loud, energetic, and instrument-driven.

These profiles confirm that genres are meaningfully separated in audio-feature space, which benefits clustering-based recommenders.

We also identify the most distinctive features per genre. For example:

  • Rap: speechiness, tempo, loudness
  • EDM: tempo, loudness, instrumentalness
  • R&B: tempo, energy variations
  • Rock: loudness and lower danceability

Such distinctive patterns help justify weighting or normalization choices in later modeling.

4. Feature Engineering

Raw features rarely provide optimal inputs for machine learning models.
Feature engineering helps transform, scale, and combine features so that our recommendation algorithms can better capture meaningful musical patterns.
In this section, we focus on normalization, dimensionality reduction, and composite feature creation.

4.1 Feature Normalization

Audio features in our dataset operate on very different scales.
For example:

  • Tempo: typically ranges from 50200 BPM
  • Danceability: always between 0 and 1

Without normalization, large-scale features (like tempo) can dominate distance-based similarity calculations.

Example:

Song A tempo = 120, danceability = 0.8
Song B tempo = 121, danceability = 0.3

If unscaled, the 1 BPM tempo difference may outweigh the 0.5 danceability difference, leading to misleading similarity scores.

In[26]:

Key Observations

  • Raw features vary dramatically in scale.
    Loudness spans nearly 50 dB, while danceability and energy remain within [0, 1].
    Without scaling, large-range features dominate similarity calculations.

  • StandardScaler centers features around zero and preserves outlier structure.
    This can be useful for models sensitive to variance, but it still allows large values (e.g., loudness) to influence distances disproportionately.

  • MinMaxScaler compresses all features into the [0, 1] interval.
    This makes each audio attribute contribute more evenly to the similarity metric, which is desirable for recommendation engines based on cosine similarity or Euclidean distance.

Because the majority of Spotify audio features are already bounded, MinMaxScaler provides the most intuitive and stable representation for content-based similarity.

This visualization validates our choice of using MinMax scaling for audio features in our recommendation system.

Although we start with nine audio features, several of them carry overlapping information

4.3 Creating Composite Features

Sometimes combinations of features better capture musical qualities than individual attributes.
Based on musical intuition, we engineer several domain-inspired composite features:

In[28]:
df_spotify['energy_danceability'] = df_spotify['energy'] * df_spotify['danceability']
df_spotify['valence_energy'] = df_spotify['valence'] * df_spotify['energy']
df_spotify['acoustic_score'] = (df_spotify['acousticness'] - df_spotify['energy']) / 2
df_spotify['party_score'] = (df_spotify['danceability'] + df_spotify['energy'] + df_spotify['valence']) / 3
df_spotify['chill_score'] = (df_spotify['acousticness'] + (1 - df_spotify['energy']) + df_spotify['instrumentalness']) / 3
df_spotify['workout_score'] = (df_spotify['energy'] + df_spotify['tempo']/200 + df_spotify['loudness']/100) / 3

5. Building Recommendation Models

In this section, we implement three complementary approaches to music recommendation.
Each methodcontent-based filtering, clustering, and hybrid scoringoffers different strengths and weaknesses.
Understanding these trade-offs is essential for evaluating real-world recommender systems.

5.1 Content-Based Filtering with Cosine Similarity

Core idea: Recommend songs whose audio features are most similar to the songs a user already likes.

How It Works

  1. Represent each track as a vector of normalized audio features.
  2. Compute cosine similarity between the target track and all other tracks.
  3. Recommend the songs with the highest similarity scores.

Cosine similarity is ideal for this task because it captures how directionally similar feature vectors are, regardless of their magnitude.

Advantages

  • No cold start for items: New songs with audio features can be recommended immediately.
  • Transparent: We can explain why a track was recommended (e.g., similar energy and danceability).
  • User independence: Works even when a user has liked only one song.

Limitations

  • Can be narrow: Often recommends songs that sound too similar.
  • No collective insight: Does not leverage what other listeners enjoy.
  • Risk of filter bubbles: Users may miss surprising or diverse content.

Content-based filtering forms the backbone of many modern music systems, especially for early personalization.

In[29]:
content_features = audio_features + composite_features
feature_matrix_content = df_spotify[content_features].reset_index(drop=True)

display(Markdown("Calculating cosine similarity matrix..."))
cosine_sim_matrix = cosine_similarity(feature_matrix_content)
display(Markdown(f"Similarity matrix shape: {cosine_sim_matrix.shape}"))

track_indices = pd.Series(df_spotify.index, index=df_spotify['track_name']).to_dict()

def get_content_based_recommendations(track_name, n_recommendations=10, show_features=False):
    if track_name not in track_indices:
        possible_matches = [t for t in track_indices.keys() if track_name.lower() in t.lower()]
        if possible_matches:
            display(Markdown(f"Track '{track_name}' not found. Did you mean one of these?"))
            for i, match in enumerate(possible_matches[:5], 1):
                display(Markdown(f"  {i}. {match}"))
            return None
        else:
            display(Markdown(f"Track '{track_name}' not found in dataset."))
            return None
    
    idx = track_indices[track_name]
    sim_scores = list(enumerate(cosine_sim_matrix[idx]))
    sim_scores = sorted(sim_scores, key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)[1:n_recommendations+1]
    track_idxs = [i[0] for i in sim_scores]
    similarity_scores = [i[1] for i in sim_scores]
    
    recommendations = df_spotify.iloc[track_idxs][['track_name', 'track_artist', 
                                                    'playlist_genre', 'track_popularity']].copy()
    recommendations['similarity_score'] = similarity_scores
    recommendations = recommendations.reset_index(drop=True)
    recommendations.index += 1
    
    input_track = df_spotify[df_spotify['track_name'] == track_name].iloc[0]
    display(Markdown("#### Input Track"))
    display(Markdown(f"Track: {input_track['track_name']}"))
    display(Markdown(f"Artist: {input_track['track_artist']}"))
    display(Markdown(f"Genre: {input_track['playlist_genre']}"))
    display(Markdown(f"Popularity: {input_track['track_popularity']}"))
    
    display(Markdown(f"#### Top {n_recommendations} Recommendations"))
    display(recommendations.style.set_caption("Recommended Tracks with Content Based Similarity Scores"))
    
    if show_features:
        input_features = df_spotify.loc[idx, audio_features]
        rec_features = df_spotify.iloc[track_idxs[0], :][audio_features]
        comparison_df = pd.DataFrame({
            'Input Track': input_features,
            'Top Recommendation': rec_features,
            'Difference': abs(input_features - rec_features)
        })
        display(Markdown("##### Audio Feature Comparision"))
        display(comparison_df.round(3).style.set_caption("Input Track vs Top Recommendation"))
    
    return recommendations

test_track = df_spotify['track_name'].iloc[100]
recommendations_content = get_content_based_recommendations(test_track, n_recommendations=10, show_features=True)

5.2 Clustering-Based Recommendations

Core idea: Group songs into clusters based on audio similarity, then recommend tracks from the same cluster.

Clustering creates a high-level structure of the musical landscape.
Two songs might not have the highest cosine similarity but still belong to the same musical neighborhood.

Why Clustering Helps

  • Improved diversity: Recommendations come from a broader but relevant pool.
  • Scalability: Once clusters are computed, recommending within them is extremely fast.
  • Interpretability: Clusters often correspond to musical styles or moods.
In[30]:
inertias = []
K_range = range(2, 15)

display(Markdown("Finding optimal number of clusters..."))
for k in K_range:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42, n_init=10)
    kmeans.fit(feature_matrix_content)
    inertias.append(kmeans.inertia_)

def get_cluster_based_recommendations(track_name, n_recommendations=10):
    if track_name not in track_indices:
        display(Markdown(f"Track '{track_name}' not found."))
        return None
    
    idx = track_indices[track_name]
    track_cluster = df_spotify.iloc[idx]['cluster']
    
    cluster_tracks = df_spotify[
        (df_spotify['cluster'] == track_cluster) & 
        (df_spotify.index != idx)
    ]
    
    recommendations = cluster_tracks.nlargest(n_recommendations, 'track_popularity')[
        ['track_name', 'track_artist', 'playlist_genre', 'track_popularity', 'cluster']
    ].copy()
    
    recommendations = recommendations.reset_index(drop=True)
    recommendations.index += 1
    
    display(Markdown(f"#### Cluster Based Recommendation (Cluster {track_cluster})"))
    display(recommendations.style.set_caption(f"Top {n_recommendations} Tracks from Cluster {track_cluster}"))
    
    return recommendations

recommendations_cluster = get_cluster_based_recommendations(test_track, n_recommendations=10)

5.3 Hybrid Recommendation System

Core idea: Combine content similarity with cluster-level structure for more balanced recommendations.

Hybrid models are widely used in production (e.g., Spotify, YouTube) because they integrate multiple signals:

Why Hybrid Works Well

  • Balances accuracy and diversity: Content similarity ensures relevance; clusters ensure variety.
  • More robust: Reduces weaknesses of single-method systems.
  • Better personalization: Captures both fine-grained and broad musical characteristics.

Hybrid Scoring Formula

We combine:

  • Content similarity weight: 0.6
  • Cluster similarity weight: 0.4

Hybrid Score
= 0.6 (cosine similarity) + 0.4 (cluster match score)

A cluster match boosts songs that share broader musical context, even if theyre not the top cosine matches.

In[31]:
def get_hybrid_recommendations(track_name, n_recommendations=10, content_weight=0.6, cluster_weight=0.4):
    if track_name not in track_indices:
        display(Markdown(f"Track '{track_name}' not found."))
        return None
    
    idx = track_indices[track_name]
    track_cluster = df_spotify.iloc[idx]['cluster']
    
    content_scores = cosine_sim_matrix[idx]
    cluster_scores = (df_spotify['cluster'] == track_cluster).astype(float).values
    hybrid_scores = (content_weight * content_scores) + (cluster_weight * cluster_scores)
    
    hybrid_scores[idx] = -1
    top_indices = hybrid_scores.argsort()[-n_recommendations:][::-1]
    
    recommendations = df_spotify.iloc[top_indices][
        ['track_name', 'track_artist', 'playlist_genre', 'track_popularity', 'cluster']
    ].copy()
    
    recommendations['hybrid_score'] = hybrid_scores[top_indices]
    recommendations['content_similarity'] = content_scores[top_indices]
    recommendations['same_cluster'] = (df_spotify.iloc[top_indices]['cluster'] == track_cluster).values
    
    recommendations = recommendations.reset_index(drop=True)
    recommendations.index += 1
    
    display(Markdown(f"####  Top Hybrid Recommended Tracks(Content: {content_weight}, Cluster: {cluster_weight})"))
    display(recommendations)
    
    return recommendations

recommendations_hybrid = get_hybrid_recommendations(test_track, n_recommendations=10)

5.4 Genre-Based Filtering

While content-based similarity captures fine-grained audio characteristics, many listeners prefer recommendations that stay within a specific genre or mood.
Genre-based filtering adds this control by restricting recommendations to songs belonging to a particular genre.

Core Idea

Recommend only songs from a chosen genre, ranked by cosine similarity.

This approach is useful when:

  • A user wants more songs in a familiar genre
  • Genre-specific playlists are being generated
  • We want to avoid cross-genre drift (e.g., recommending EDM songs for a jazz listener)
In[32]:
def get_genre_filtered_recommendations(track_name, genre=None, n_recommendations=10):
    if track_name not in track_indices:
        display(Markdown(f"Track '{track_name}' not found."))
        return None
    
    idx = track_indices[track_name]
    
    if genre is None:
        genre = df_spotify.iloc[idx]['playlist_genre']
    
    genre_mask = df_spotify['playlist_genre'] == genre
    
    sim_scores = []
    for i, is_in_genre in enumerate(genre_mask):
        if is_in_genre and i != idx:
            sim_scores.append((i, cosine_sim_matrix[idx][i]))
    
    sim_scores = sorted(sim_scores, key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)[:n_recommendations]
    
    track_idxs = [i[0] for i in sim_scores]
    similarity_scores = [i[1] for i in sim_scores]
    
    recommendations = df_spotify.iloc[track_idxs][
        ['track_name', 'track_artist', 'playlist_genre', 'playlist_subgenre', 'track_popularity']
    ].copy()
    recommendations['similarity_score'] = similarity_scores
    recommendations = recommendations.reset_index(drop=True)
    recommendations.index += 1
    
    display(Markdown(f"#### Genre-Filtered Recommendations (Genre: {genre})"))
    display(recommendations.style.set_caption(f"Top {n_recommendations} Tracks in Genre '{genre}'"))
    
    return recommendations

recommendations_genre = get_genre_filtered_recommendations(test_track, n_recommendations=10)

6. Evaluation and Results

How do we know if our recommendations are actually useful?
Visual inspection is helpful, but not enough. In this section we:

  • Quantify diversity of recommendation lists
  • Simulate different user profiles
  • Examine cold-start behavior for low-popularity tracks

Together, these analyses give a more complete picture of system quality.

6.1 Recommendation Diversity Analysis

Recommender systems often suffer from the filter bubble problem: they keep recommending items that look almost identical to what the user already knows.
To study this, we compare several models using a small set of diversity metrics.

In[33]:
def calculate_diversity_metrics(recommendations, input_idx):
    rec_indices = recommendations.index.tolist()
    rec_features = feature_matrix_content.iloc[rec_indices]
    inter_sim_matrix = cosine_similarity(rec_features)
    
    mask = ~np.eye(inter_sim_matrix.shape[0], dtype=bool)
    avg_inter_similarity = inter_sim_matrix[mask].mean()
    
    genres = recommendations['playlist_genre'].nunique()
    total_genres = df_spotify['playlist_genre'].nunique()
    genre_diversity = genres / total_genres
    
    pop_variance = recommendations['track_popularity'].var()
    
    return {
        'avg_inter_similarity': avg_inter_similarity,
        'genre_diversity': genre_diversity,
        'unique_genres': genres,
        'popularity_variance': pop_variance
    }


methods = {

}

Diversity summary:

  • Average inter-similarity: All methods have very similar internal similarity (~0.97), meaning individual lists remain coherent.
  • Genre diversity / unique genres:
    • Content-Based: Moderate genre diversity ( 5 genres per list).
    • Cluster-Based: Lower diversity ( 3 genres) recommendations tend to stay inside a few clusters.
    • Hybrid: Highest diversity and coherence, similar to content-based but with broader spread.
    • Genre-Filtered: Single-genre lists by design (1 genre) maximum stylistic consistency, minimum diversity.
  • Popularity variance:
    • Cluster-Based: Very low variance recommendations cluster around similar popularity levels.
    • Hybrid: Highest variance mixes mainstream and niche songs.
    • Content-Based / Genre-Filtered: Moderate variance.

Takeaway:

  • Cluster-based and genre-filtered models excel at coherence,
  • Hybrid and content-based models provide better variety and include both popular and lesser-known tracks.
    Balancing these metrics is key to avoiding filter bubbles while keeping recommendations relevant.

6.2 User Profile Simulation

To check whether our system adapts to different musical tastes, we simulate three user profiles:

  • Rap-focused user
  • Pop-focused user
  • EDM-focused user

For each profile, we:

  1. Sample ~20 liked songs from the target genre.
  2. Build an average user feature profile.
  3. Generate content-based and hybrid recommendations.
  4. Measure how closely recommendations match the user profile.
In[34]:
np.random.seed(42)

def create_user_profile(genre, n_liked_songs=20):
    genre_songs = df_spotify[df_spotify['playlist_genre'] == genre]
    liked_songs = genre_songs.sample(n=min(n_liked_songs, len(genre_songs)))
    return liked_songs.index.tolist()

test_genres = df_spotify['playlist_genre'].value_counts().head(3).index.tolist()
user_profiles = {genre: create_user_profile(genre) for genre in test_genres}

def evaluate_recommendations_for_user(user_liked_indices, recommendations_func, **kwargs):
    user_feature_profile = feature_matrix_content.loc[user_liked_indices].mean()
    
    seed_idx = np.random.choice(user_liked_indices)
    
    try:
        seed_track = df_spotify.loc[seed_idx, 'track_name']
    except KeyError:
        valid_indices = [idx for idx in user_liked_indices if idx in df_spotify.index]
        if not valid_indices:
            display(Markdown(f"No valid indices found for user profile"))
            return None
        seed_idx = np.random.choice(valid_indices)
        seed_track = df_spotify.loc[seed_idx, 'track_name']
    
    recs = recommendations_func(seed_track, **kwargs)
    
    if recs is None:
        return None
    
    try:
        rec_features = feature_matrix_content.loc[recs.index]
    except KeyError:
        rec_features = feature_matrix_content.iloc[recs.index.tolist()]
    
    profile_similarities = cosine_similarity([user_feature_profile], rec_features)[0]
    
    return {
        'avg_profile_match': profile_similarities.mean(),
        'min_profile_match': profile_similarities.min(),
        'max_profile_match': profile_similarities.max(),
        'recommendations': recs
    }


for genre, user_indices in user_profiles.items():
    display(Markdown(f"#### {genre.upper()} User Profile"))
    display(Markdown(f"Liked songs: {len(user_indices)}"))
    
    content_eval = evaluate_recommendations_for_user(
        user_indices, get_content_based_recommendations, n_recommendations=10
    )

        user_indices, get_hybrid_recommendations, n_recommendations=10
    )
    
    if content_eval and hybrid_eval:
        display(Markdown(f"Content-Based Avg Match: {content_eval['avg_profile_match']:.4f}"))
        display(Markdown(f"Hybrid Avg Match: {hybrid_eval['avg_profile_match']:.4f}"))

6.3 Cold-Start Analysis

A classic challenge in recommender systems is the cold start problem:
How do we recommend items with little or no interaction history?

To test this, we select tracks at different popularity levels:

  • Low / zero popularity (04)
  • Medium ( 3050)
  • High ( 6080)
  • Very high ( 70+)

For each seed track, we generate content-based recommendations and inspect:

  • Genres returned
  • Popularity levels
  • Similarity scores

7. Insights and Conclusions

Key Findings

Through our analysis and the implementation of several recommendation strategies, we can summarize a few core insights about music recommendation systems.

7.1 Feature Importance and Correlations

Our exploratory analysis showed that some audio features are strongly related:

  • Energy and Loudness have a strong positive correlation (r 0.68), meaning they largely describe the same notion of intensity.
  • Energy and Acousticness have a strong negative correlation (r 0.55), placing loud, electronic tracks at one end and quiet, acoustic tracks at the other.
  • Other relationships (e.g., valence and danceability) are more moderate, but still meaningful.

These patterns imply that certain features are partially redundant.
Using all of them naively can overweight specific aspects of the sound.
Our PCA results confirmed this: 7 principal components explain ~90% of the variance, indicating that the 9-dimensional feature space can be compressed with limited information loss.

7.2 Genre Profiles and Musical Identity

Averaging audio features by genre revealed clear genre-specific audio signatures:

  • EDM: very high energy and tempo, low acousticness.
  • Latin: high danceability and valence; typically upbeat.
  • Pop: balanced, moderately high energy and danceability.
  • R&B: somewhat lower energy, higher acousticness and speechiness.
  • Rap: high speechiness and danceability, with strong rhythmic focus.
  • Rock: high energy and loudness, but generally less danceable than EDM/Latin.

These profiles help explain why clustering works: clusters align with recognizable musical neighborhoods.
They also motivate genre-aware or genre-filtered recommendation modes for users who want to stay within certain stylistic boundaries.

7.3 The Popularity Paradox

When we correlated audio features with Spotifys popularity score, we found that:

  • All correlations were weak (roughly between 0.12 and +0.09).
  • The strongest relationships were slightly negative (e.g., instrumentalness vs. popularity), but still small in magnitude.

In other words, popular songs do not share a strong, simple audio signature.
Popularity is likely driven by factors that are not present in our dataset: marketing, artist fame, playlists, social trends, etc.

This has two implications:

  1. Content-based recommenders alone will not perfectly mimic charts or mainstream popularity.
  2. In a production system, it is natural to combine content features with behavioral signals (streams, skips, saves) for better ranking.

Our project stays on the content side, but the results clearly point toward the value of adding collaborative and temporal signals in future work.

7.4 Recommendation Diversity Trade-offs

We evaluated four approaches: Content-Based, Cluster-Based, Hybrid, and Genre-Filtered.
Using our diversity metrics, we observed that:

  • Content-Based produced coherent, relevant lists with moderate genre diversity.
  • Cluster-Based tended to stay inside a smaller set of genres and popularity bands, leading to lower genre diversity but very stable neighborhoods.
  • Hybrid (content + cluster) preserved high average similarity while increasing diversity and popularity spread, mixing mainstream and niche tracks.
  • Genre-Filtered intentionally restricted results to a single genre, maximizing stylistic consistency at the cost of diversity.

The best method depends on the product goal:

  • For More Like This or artist-radio style features content-based or genre-filtered is ideal.
  • For discovery playlists (e.g., a mini Discover Weekly) hybrid models are more suitable, as they balance similarity with variety.

7.5 User Profiles and Cold Start

Our simulated user profiles (rap, pop, EDM) showed that:

  • Both content-based and hybrid models achieved high average similarity between recommendations and the users feature profile ( 0.950.98).
  • Hybrid recommendations were more likely to include cross-genre tracks that still sound similar (e.g., EDM songs recommended for a rap profile when they share energy and rhythm), offering controlled exploration.

In our cold-start analysis, we examined seeds across popularity levels:

  • Even for tracks with popularity = 0, the system found high-similarity neighbors (cosine similarity 0.99).
  • Recommendation quality did not collapse for low-popularity songs because our methods rely on audio content, not usage history.

This demonstrates a key advantage of content-based systems:
they naturally handle new or rarely played items, which traditional collaborative filtering struggles with.

Limitations and Future Directions

While our engine performs well as a content-driven prototype, several limitations remain:

  • No temporal dynamics: We do not model how tastes change over time or how songs trend and decay in popularity.
  • Limited context awareness: Our system does not distinguish between use cases such as studying, workouts, or parties, even though context heavily influences music choice.
  • No true collaborative filtering: We lack useritem interaction data, so we cannot capture people who liked X also liked Y effects.
  • Scalability considerations: Our experiments are on ~30k tracks. Production systems must handle millions of songs and users, requiring approximate nearest neighbor search, incremental clustering, and efficient storage.

Future extensions could include:

  • Incorporating user feedback logs to build hybrid contentcollaborative models.
  • Learning context-aware recommendations (time of day, device, activity).
  • Using more expressive audio embeddings (e.g., deep learningbased representations) instead of hand-engineered features.
  • Deploying approximate similarity search (e.g., FAISS, Annoy) to scale recommendations to catalogs with millions of items.

Despite these limitations, our project demonstrates that with a well-curated dataset, thoughtful feature engineering, and multiple recommendation strategies, we can build a robust and interpretable music recommendation engine that balances personalization, diversity, and cold-start performance.

Conclusion

Building an effective music recommendation system requires balancing several competing objectives: relevance vs. diversity, exploitation vs. exploration, and personalization vs. generalization. Throughout this tutorial, we demonstrated how to address these challenges using real Spotify data and a combination of algorithmic approaches.

The recommendation engine developed here:

  • Analyzed a dataset of nearly 30,000 songs across multiple genres
  • Implemented content-based, cluster-based, and hybrid recommendation methods
  • Evaluated recommendation quality using both relevance and diversity metrics
  • Identified meaningful patterns in audio features and genre characteristics
  • Produced insights that can translate directly to real-world recommender systems

At its core, music recommendation is about connecting listeners with songs they genuinely enjoywhether that means reinforcing what they already like or helping them discover something unexpected. Data science gives us the tools to make these decisions at scale, but the real craft lies in knowing when to lean into familiarity and when to encourage exploration.

As you continue building and refining recommendation systems, remember that the strongest models combine technical rigor with an understanding of human taste, context, and behavior. Keep experimenting, keep measuring, andjust like your userskeep listening.
